text.tspan: The multiboot modification for Android devices

flowRoot.flowPara: During development of applications or even of a new operating system, which may not be fully usable yet, it is possible to still have a clean version of Android installed, for when the user doesn't want to develop anything but needs a working phone instead.
Multiboot is completely ordinary feature on desktop computers, used mostly by advanced users. MultiROM brings the same level of comfort even to portable devices.

MultiROM has been developed since year 2012. It has 18 314 active installations (data from 11th June 2014) and the userbase is still growing. In 2013, a successful crowdfunding campaing took place on Indiegogo.com. Its goal was to buy a test device and to modify the code to make it more portable. Target of $500 was reached in 24 days and I have fulfilled all my commitments in pre-designeted time.

Trying out various Android ROMs or even different types of operating systems is much easier with MultiROM â you don't have to waste time making backup and then restoring it again anymore!

True, on desktop computers, multiboot is used almost exclusively by advanced users, so it might seem pointless to bring it to Android devices.

But due to its openness, a similar group of developers and enthusiasts has formed around Android. This large community of potential users isÂ growing every day and would very much benefit from a multiboot modification.
That is why I have created MultiROM.

Because MultiROM is a low-level software modification, it is not possible to support all Android devices with a single version. I personally support three phones and two tablets. MultiROM is a software modification which enables the installation of multiple operating systems at once, just like on PC.
It is useful mainly toÂ advanced users, but compared to similar modifications, MultiROM isÂ very easy to use.

Dozens of videos, articles and tutorials have been created by third parties, so the users have plenty to go on in case of any problems, questions or uncertainties.
Even if they fail to find the solution for their problem, they can ask in the official forum threads, where I or some other member of the community are likely to help.
MultiROM has been widely adopted in the community ofÂ Android enthusiasts and developers.
AÂ person interested in the community's creations often has to backup and restore their system just to try out that new thing somebody just released.
That takes a lot of time andÂ space, but with MultiROM they can just install it as aÂ secondary and delete it when they're done â orÂ keep it around, always just one reboot away.
MultiROM supports not just Android, but basically anything that runs onÂ given device. That means you can safely try out new and exciting operating systems.
Just install them as secondary systems, and your main Android installation that you need toÂ work properly all the time remains intact and you can reboot into it whenever you wish.
Developers can use MultiROM to install several different versions ofÂ Android to use either for app development or toÂ test multiple builds of the whole OS.
It saves a lot of time because they don't have to re-flash toÂ go back to the previous version andÂ still have the main system fully working despite the other systems not being functional.
